         b'eography category-info-overload category-research category-taxonomy"'
         b' id="post-1003">\n\t\t\t<h2>Intelligence-gathering by sneakernet</h2'
         b'>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>A <a href="http://www.c'
         b'nas.org/files/documents/publications/AfghanIntel_Flynn_Jan2010_code5'
         b'07_voices.pdf">new report by senior US intelligence officers</a> rec'
         b'ommends sweeping changes to intelligence-gathering practices in Afgh'
         b'anistan. The two most interesting recommendations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>'
         b' Intelligence work should be divided along geographic, rather than f'
         b'unctional, lines. &#8220;The alternative \xe2\x80\x93 having all '
         b'analysts study an entire province or region through the lens of a na'
         b'rrow, functional line (e.g. one analyst covers governance, another s'
         b'tudies narcotics trafficking, a third looks at insurgent networks, e'
         b'tc) \xe2\x80\x93 isn\xe2\x80\x99t working.&#8221; (p4)\n</li>\n<li> '
         b'Analysts should aggregate intelligence by regularly travelling to vi'
         b'sit those who collect it. &#8220;Information essential to the succes'
         b'sful conduct of a counterinsurgency is ripe for retrieval, but analy'
         b'sts that remain confined to restricted-access buildings in Kabul or '
         b'on Bagram and Kandahar Airfields cannot access it.&#8221; (p17) The '
         b'internet is not suitable for this purpose because &#8220;vital infor'
         b'mation piles up in obscure SharePoint sites, inaccessible hard drive'
         b's, and other digital junkyards.&#8221;\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The first '
         b'point interests me because it suggests that problem-solving doesn&#8'
         b'217;t always scale through specialisation, as tends to be assumed in'
         b' academia: when the flow of information is constricted, a geographic'
         b'ally-organised hierarchy of generalists may be more effective than a'
         b' taxonomically-organised hierarchy of specialists.</p>\n<p>The se'
         b'cond point bears more directly on mobblog&#8217;s research interests'
         b' (though I&#8217;m <b>not</b> suggesting we should design communicat'
         b'ion systems for the US military): manual aggregation and curation of'
         b' information are still necessary, even when that information is in d'
         b'igital form. More surprisingly, the oldest method of aggregation &#8'
         b'211; sneakernet &#8211; remains the most reliable.</p>\n<p>The is'
         b'sues discussed in the report might seem specific to the chaotic and '
         b'poorly connected environment of Afghanistan, but I want to argue tha'
         b't the fundamental problem &#8211; finding relevant information in a '
         b'shifting sea of circumstances, practices, organisational structures '
         b'and data formats &#8211; exists everywhere, and is not solved by bet'
         b'ter connectivity, nor by making everything digital.</p>\n<p>David'
         b' Weinberger has suggested that in the digital realm, <a href="http:/'
         b'/video.google.com/videoplay?docid=2159021324062223592">tags will rep'
         b'lace taxonomies</a> and it will no longer be necessary to separate t'
         b'he organisation of information from its retrieval; but while the not'
         b'ion of a &#8216;hierarchy of generalists&#8217; does cast doubt on t'
         b'he usefulness of <i>a priori</i> taxonomies, the recommendation of m'
         b'anual data collection and curation is directly opposed to Weinberger'
         b'&#8217;s &#8216;tag soup&#8217; approach.</p>\n<p>Does this simpl'
         b'y reflect a lack of tools (or, God help us, <a href="http://www.w3.o'
         b'rg/2001/sw/">standards</a>), or is the complexity of real-world info'
         b'rmation as irreducible to tags as it is to taxonomies? Anyone who&#8'
         b'217;s used Google Images will recognise the difficulty of applying t'
         b'ags to non-textual data; assuming the sea never stops shifting, will'
         b' the extraction of relevant knowledge from information always be a m'
         b'atter of &#8211; well &#8211; intelligence?</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t'
